{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536849"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:10:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:10:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15816"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15816","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15816"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.78,0.02,0.01,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8507"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105781"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8507","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8507"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15816"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88249"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"282"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1106"},{"type":"tags","id":"3996"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20421"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38591"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105781","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105781"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman is an inpatient being treated for infectious colitis acquired during an overseas trip. She has a history of epilepsy and usually takes sodium valproate, but has been vomiting for three days and unable to keep down her medications. A Code Blue is called as she begins having generalised tonic-clonic seizures. Two doses of intramuscular midazolam 5 mg have been given five minutes apart with no effect. She has now been seizing continuously for eight minutes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 160/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. She is unresponsive during ongoing generalised tonic-clonic movements in all four limbs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Insert nasogastric tube for medication administration","Commence intravenous levetiracetam","Commence oral sodium valproate","Observe for 10 more minutes","Give a third dose of midazolam"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is in status epilepticus, having failed to respond to two appropriate doses of benzodiazepines. Status epilepticus is a medical emergency associated with significant morbidity and mortality if not treated promptly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous levetiracetam\u003C/strong\u003E is an appropriate second-line agent for status epilepticus. It should be administered promptly when benzodiazepines have failed, while simultaneously arranging urgent anaesthetic/intensive care review. The longer the duration of status epilepticus, the more difficult it becomes to terminate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA third dose of midazolam\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as it is unlikely to be effective if two doses have failed, and may contribute to respiratory depression. The focus should shift to second-line agents.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral sodium valproate\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate in active seizures as the patient cannot safely swallow. Additionally, oral preparations would have delayed onset of action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObserving for 10 more minutes\u003C/strong\u003E would constitute dangerous delay in management. Status epilepticus requires prompt escalation of therapy to prevent neurological damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInserting a nasogastric tube\u003C/strong\u003E during active seizures would be dangerous and could cause trauma. Additionally, enteral medication administration is not appropriate in this emergency situation where rapid drug levels are required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter commencing second-line therapy, the patient will require close monitoring, likely in an intensive care setting. Investigations should include antiepileptic drug levels, electrolytes, glucose, and consideration of neuroimaging once stabilised.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Status epilepticus is defined as continuous seizure activity lasting more than 5 minutes or recurrent seizures without recovery of consciousness between episodes.","After two doses of benzodiazepines for status epilepticus, second-line anticonvulsants should be administered and intensive care support sought.","Delays in progressing to second-line therapy in status epilepticus are associated with worse outcomes."],"references":["Wylie T, Sandhu DS, Murr NI. Status epilepticus. [Updated 2023 May 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430686/","Crawshaw AA, Cock HR, Smith M, Patten AR. Medical management of status epilepticus: emergency room to intensive care unit. Seizure. 2020;75:145\u2013152. Available at: https://www.seizure-journal.com/article/S1059-1311(19)30204-3/fulltext","Jones CL, Koios J. Algorithm for the treatment of status epilepticus: an Australian perspective. Intern Med J. 2016 Apr;46(4):500-3. Available at: https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/imj.12997"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88249"}},"question":{"data":{"type":